commit.message:
router: be more careful with freeing addrinfo

When saddr is NULL (because a host failed to resolve previously) we
should not try to freeaddrinfo it, in particular because unlike glibc,
the libc may not ignore NULL here as POSIX doesn't demand that.  At
least musl has this behaviour.

Issue: https://github.com/grobian/carbon-c-relay/issues/455
Signed-off-by: Fabian Groffen <grobian@gentoo.org>

commit.message:
router: don't route metrics to a failed any_of destination, #454

Make sure we respect the failed state of destinations so we don't
introduce artificial lag, and possibly an avalanche situation multiple
times which causes metric drops.
When an any_of destination fails and after a brief period of it not
returning, the destination is flagged as failed, and other destinations
from the any_of cluster will receive the metrics.  In the meanwhile the
queue from the now failed destination will be offloaded to other
destinations (causing a spike of traffic).

Closes: https://github.com/grobian/carbon-c-relay/issues/454
Signed-off-by: Fabian Groffen <grobian@gentoo.org>

commit.message:
collector: fix behaviour regarding stdio streams when submission + debug

Our tests use -s -d to enable submission mode and debug.  This
previously should enable iostat-like output from the relay, but due to
stdio buffering on most libcs, this was invisible (a bug).  Using musl
libc, a different buffering strategy reveals we were actually writing
the statistics header and data, which for tests is undesirable.

So, rework the iostat-like behaviour into a new -S option, that implies
submission mode (-s).  While at it, cleanup a lot of cruft from old mode
setting that is no longer in use.

Bug: https://bugs.gentoo.org/833846
Signed-off-by: Fabian Groffen <grobian@gentoo.org>

commit.message:
test/create-self-cert: add script to generate a new SSL cert

SSL is too smart to work with faketime (luckily) so just generate a new
cert every time we run tests.  This doesn't take too long, and should
ensure the cert never expired when we run tests.
